\\"isError\\\": false, \\\"timestamp\\\": 1777654848601}]}\\n4379:[thinking] I'm identifying a possible issue with `ClassLoader.getSystemResourceAsStream` when it's called from the bootstrap-loaded MessageCatalog, since the system loader can still load resources. Now, because the dtd-parser jar was boot appended, the MessageCatalog will load normally from bootstrap. I'm considering if the dynamic access on line 489 can see that it's loaded from bootstrap. I wonder if coverage instrumentation affects accessing line 506 and how dynamic report filters might influence what's tracked. It looks like I need to check if resource access returns non-null and if `Class.forName(name)` uses the caller's classloader.\\n4392:[recv] {\\\"type\\\": \\\"message_end\\\", \\\"message\\\": {\\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\", \\\"content\\\": [{\\\"type\\\": \\\"thinking\\\", \\\"thinking\\\": \\\"**Checking Gradle source sets**\\\\n\\\\nI'm going through the source sets in Checkstyle and wondering if I should check bootstrapProbe too, since it might not have any assertions. There’s a potential concern with the new Gradle sourceSet creating bootstrapProbeJar. I'm thinking about how native tests reference BootstrapMessageCatalogProbe, and if that could affect loading during regular JVM tests. It's a bit complex, especially with how classes are resolved, but I believe I’m keeping it all in check regarding the classpath.\\\\n\\\\n**Investigating ClassLoader behavior**\\\\n\\\\nI'm identifying a possible issue with `ClassLoader.getSystemResourceAsStream` when it's called from the bootstrap-loaded MessageCatalog, since the system loader can still load resources. Now, because the dtd-parser jar was boot appended, the MessageCatalog will load normally from bootstrap. I'm considering if the dynamic access on line 489 can see that it's loaded from bootstrap. I wonder if coverage instrumentation affects accessing line 506 and how dynamic report filters might influence what's tracked. It looks like I need to check if resource access returns non-null and if `Class.forName(name)` uses the caller's classloader.\\\\n\\\\n**Understanding Class.forName behavior**\\\\n\\\\nI’m thinking about how `Class.forName(String)` uses the defining classloader of the caller, which in this case is the current class, MessageCatalog. Since MessageCatalog is boot-loaded, it will use the bootstrap loader instead of the app loader. Uh oh! So when it tries to load `Messages_es`, it’s attempting to do so with the bootstrap context. This feels a bit tricky, as I need to ensure the right loader is being utilized in this scenario.\\\", \\\"thinkingSignature\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"rs_053f396fbad82c020169f4dc41e38c81939bd4ddde670183cb\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"reasoning\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"encrypted_content\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"gAAAAABp9NxOY4Iq3W_RhDpPnQ3KldUE-mPUAdJKbKuRl3U5ORm0wzmZM6bZzZUm9ttapydPGT6knBrozyLXtglJGFpgYxIxqqviwKnU8aijmy5yFj70pGmlv5ZbUlO8pC1mo1xn8aFRj9fDUnYGBPb2Ov5kglf7Yh3-SyQ6UcFi7bIe_brvp9DPB39ocneX7GqMQAKsZv_I5TlJSMA3x5XF10rpKEsDQDwddwVDQWEZlbq5Lbl29IrGzEwWrn7sTF0OxGFZ4vGexxB1-8MQFWhDsBhzJBc2dMeqrt-sM5sc_4C4XJJMXsjqdKKc3tXFQAfZJ_I6Ec3picaIlniipJiGW-IrkVoLrIlDfPWkCuxVmVO6QmEeYCnAGb816r5Te1VU3ub3lY-K9B8GVGkIP-yRWR2cNX4NM2jGotWrKrShC__0FSdRoHNLQstW2vaIW1ieZpVUejYmOK6agcX9fzeFuj98YSC46aXGU3NIG7Bw7ujfX6F18vBpE9npOdxTla1hbFwkiI5QjmtqKDrVbbkoVFJoeFNBpwUxVQBqFTy3aE86lul81SzZpBZQzQ0RavmPK7eG9bO2wRIy-SG418KcP5g646Ga0WoaKwblLmKePpgosCWCX4hCkSiRBMh1HDzSIXKnyG5_nmn0rFFXfIzNLnvTrSRR2XO4ndRo5hDpesl74yKCL6PiX5demQmzFzrVqNEDd1EadrKlass7cDEJksNH9CxB9XjTEIDuE_RkuKjcA6xdKReWEqvDPCa8SrQpHsp_XmhGs4rWZ4mrvBnzzxpSqzd655-nAhj8zqPai89OxwUsNzAv7RC4mDVSznWG8_hNeBmrV6lz9Cdtr_dQDH5pCjq9Duuv0vwImaUorv5JXJ_Oo9nWE0dJGXH3TSym69gy2vcw5pHv96hMUX2qUPTmAERQYNS6ztoHQYyzYCUGIDt0_5z_NNqdywWP20u5sUN07iDPKoLmNFE6LrxgnTQKO8050zADWSj00sXmdr7mI5GkOnT_z6ilIl3eiuiX4MK3u_CXfOJrw7AYd0bg_LhtbmPM395vkX0qTKLVmRebyeLoX016jFNRWrNhRhEtfQwMQv6SKjT_w-vRkRDOyRoTG2yTs3voqAcCJ2DeL6DnFSc-EnrftHmp2Xnq8yaDa_UFTJHx4f_EufU