e it might not have any assertions. There’s a potential concern with the new Gradle sourceSet creating bootstrapProbeJar. I'm thinking about how native tests reference BootstrapMessageCatalogProbe, and if that could affect loading during regular JVM tests. It's a bit complex, especially with how classes are resolved, but I believe I’m keeping it all in check regarding the classpath.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Investigating ClassLoader behavior**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm identifying a possible issue with `ClassLoader.getSystemResourceAsStream` when it's called from the bootstrap-loaded MessageCatalog, since the system loader can still load resources. Now, because the dtd-parser jar was boot appended, the MessageCatalog will load normally from bootstrap. I'm considering if the dynamic access on line 489 can see that it's loaded from bootstrap. I wonder if coverage instrumentation affects accessing line 506 and how dynamic report filters might influence what's tracked. It looks like I need to check if resource access returns non-null and if `Class.forName(name)` uses the caller's classloader.\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"summary_text\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"**Understanding Class.forName behavior**\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI’m thinking about how `Class.forName(String)` uses the defining classloader of the caller, which in this case is the current class, MessageCatalog. Since MessageCatalog is boot-loaded, it will use the bootstrap loader instead of the app loader. Uh oh! So when it tries to load `Messages_es`, it’s attempting to do so with the bootstrap context. This feels a bit tricky, as I need to ensure the right loader is being utilized in this scenario.\\\\\\\"}]}\\\"}, {\\\"type\\\": \\\"toolCall\\\", \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_lTWH0ousJs0wCJMiwvu1PnVT|fc_053f396fbad82c020169f4dc4eb2cc81939397a265cc3c4098\\\", \\\"name\\\": \\\"write\\\", \\\"arguments\\\": {\\\"path\\\": \\\"tests/src/com.sun.xm